Docker Multi-Tenant Application Isolation and Orchestration
Objectives
Design and deploy a containerized multi-tenant platform with enforced network isolation between tenants using custom Docker bridge networks
Implement per-tenant CPU and memory resource quotas using Docker runtime constraints and verify enforcement under load
Orchestrate the full multi-tenant stack â applications, shared services, and a reverse proxy â using a single Docker Compose manifest with health checks
Prerequisites
Comfort navigating and editing files on a Linux command line, including writing shell scripts and reading command output
Familiarity with HTTP request/response concepts and basic networking terms such as port, IP address, and DNS resolution
Understanding of YAML indentation rules sufficient to write a valid configuration file from scratch
Lab Environment
You will work on a dedicated AWS EC2 Ubuntu instance provided by Al Nafi. The instance has a base Ubuntu installation; you will install all required tools in Task 1.

Task 1: Install and Verify the Container Toolchain
Step 1.1 â Install Docker Engine and Docker Compose Plugin
Install Docker Engine from the official Docker apt repository, then install the Compose plugin. The Docker apt repository is separate from Ubuntu's default package index and must be added manually before any Docker packages can be installed.

sudo apt-get update
sudo apt-get install -y ca-certificates curl gnupg

sudo install -m 0755 -d /etc/apt/keyrings

curl -fsSL https://download.docker.com/linux/ubuntu/gpg \
  | sudo gpg --dearmor -o /etc/apt/keyrings/docker.gpg

sudo chmod a+r /etc/apt/keyrings/docker.gpg
Official installation guide if the URL above changes: https://docs.docker.com/engine/install/ubuntu/

sudo tee /etc/apt/sources.list.d/docker.list <<'EOF'
deb [arch=amd64 signed-by=/etc/apt/keyrings/docker.gpg] https://download.docker.com/linux/ubuntu jammy stable
EOF

sudo apt-get update
sudo apt-get install -y docker-ce docker-ce-cli containerd.io docker-buildx-plugin docker-compose-plugin
