Task 2: Design and Deploy an Isolated Multi-Tenant Container Platform
Problem Statement
Design and implement a containerized platform that runs three independent tenant applications simultaneously. Each tenant must be completely isolated at the network layer â no tenant container may reach another tenant's container by name or IP address. All three applications must be reachable from the host machine on distinct ports, and a shared PostgreSQL database must be accessible only to tenants that are explicitly granted access to the shared services network.

You choose the application runtime for each tenant (Python, Node.js, Go, or any language available in a public Docker base image). Each application must expose at minimum a root endpoint (/) returning a JSON payload that identifies the tenant, and a /health endpoint returning {"status":"healthy"}. You must write a Dockerfile for each tenant from scratch â no pre-built application images.

Constraints:

Tenant networks must be named tenant-a-net, tenant-b-net, and tenant-c-net
The shared database network must be named shared-net
No tenant container may be attached to another tenant's named network
All containers must be started with --restart unless-stopped
The shared PostgreSQL container must be attached only to shared-net; at least one tenant container must also be attached to shared-net to demonstrate selective access
Acceptance Criterion 1: Running docker network inspect tenant-a-net, docker network inspect tenant-b-net, and docker network inspect tenant-c-net each shows exactly one tenant application container in the Containers field, and no tenant container appears in more than one tenant network. Running docker exec <tenant-a-container> ping -c 2 <tenant-b-container-name> must exit with a non-zero code and print a name resolution or network unreachable error, confirming cross-tenant isolation.

Acceptance Criterion 2: Running curl -sf http://localhost:8081, curl -sf http://localhost:8082, and curl -sf http://localhost:8083 each returns a JSON body containing a tenant key with a distinct value, and curl -sf http://localhost:8081/health returns {"status":"healthy"} with HTTP 200. All three commands must succeed without any Connection refused error.

Task 3: Enforce Resource Quotas and Orchestrate with Docker Compose
Problem Statement
Redesign the entire multi-tenant platform as a single Docker Compose manifest. The manifest must define all tenant applications, the shared PostgreSQL database, and an Nginx reverse proxy that routes incoming requests to the correct tenant backend based on URL path prefix (/tenant-a, /tenant-b, /tenant-c). You must write the Nginx configuration from scratch.

Every service in the manifest must declare explicit CPU and memory limits. The limits must reflect a realistic tiered model: the database receives the most resources, the reverse proxy the least, and the three tenant applications receive intermediate values that differ from one another by at least one resource dimension. All services must include a healthcheck block that Docker can use to determine container readiness.

Constraints:

The entire stack must start with a single docker compose up -d command issued from the project root
Resource limits must be declared using the deploy.resources.limits block (Compose v3.8 or later syntax)
The Nginx reverse proxy must be the only container with port 80 exposed to the host; tenant application containers must not publish any host port in the Compose manifest
The PostgreSQL container must use a named volume for data persistence; the volume must be declared in the top-level volumes block
Health checks must use curl or pg_isready as appropriate â no CMD-SHELL with true or no-op commands
Acceptance Criterion 1: After docker compose up -d, running docker compose ps shows all services in running state with health status healthy (not starting or unhealthy) within 90 seconds. Running docker compose exec shared-database pg_isready -U dbadmin must print accepting connections. Running curl -sf http://localhost/tenant-a and curl -sf http://localhost/tenant-b and curl -sf http://localhost/tenant-c must each return the corresponding tenant's JSON response through the reverse proxy.

Acceptance Criterion 2: Running docker inspect <tenant-a-service-container> --format '{{.HostConfig.Memory}}' returns a non-zero integer (confirming the memory limit is applied at the container runtime level, not only in the Compose file). Running docker inspect <database-container> --format '{{.HostConfig.Memory}}' returns a value strictly greater than the value returned for any tenant application container. Running docker compose down -v removes all containers and the named volume without error, and a subsequent docker volume ls shows no leftover volume from this project.

Expected Outcomes
A fully operational multi-tenant Docker environment in which network isolation between tenants is verifiable by failed cross-tenant ping attempts, resource quotas are confirmed by docker inspect output, and all services are reachable through the Nginx reverse proxy after a single docker compose up -d
A reproducible project directory containing all Dockerfiles, application source files, the Nginx configuration, and the Docker Compose manifest, such that tearing down the stack with docker compose down -v and restarting it with docker compose up -d produces the same healthy state without manual intervention
Conclusion
This lab required you to reason about container isolation, resource governance, and service orchestration as interconnected design decisions rather than independent steps. The network isolation model you implemented mirrors production multi-tenant SaaS architectures where tenant data-plane separation is a hard security requirement. The Docker Compose manifest you produced is the foundation for adding secrets management, TLS termination, and centralized logging as the platform matures
